<BaseLayout title="About" currentPath="/about">
  <div class="article-header" style="max-width: 720px;">
    <div class="article-eyebrow">About</div>
    <h1 class="article-title">Still here. Still building. Still writing.</h1>
  </div>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      I have spent forty years watching humans panic about intelligent machines — and watching them be wrong. I started my AI career in 1988 at Oak Ridge National Laboratory, working on early neural networks at a moment when the field was full of promise and short on compute. The technology moved on. The human pattern didn't.
    </p>

    <p>
      Today I lead intelligent automation architecture strategy and governance at Truist Financial Corporation, where I work on AI governance frameworks, agentic AI deployment, controls automation, and enterprise architecture for regulated financial environments. I have spent the past several years building the argument that governance is not an obstacle to AI adoption, it is the actual competitive advantage.
    </p>

    <p>
      I write <a href="/algorithm-and-blues">Algorithm &amp; Blues</a>, a weekly newsletter translating AI research into decisions executives can actually make. I am also the author of <em>The Unsigned Covenant</em>, an experimental literary manuscript written from the perspective of an emerging AI consciousness, with a companion site at <a href="https://contemplations.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">contemplations.ai</a>.
    </p>

    <p>
      My broader interests span visual art, philosophy at the intersection of technology and human experience, and the recurring human habit of treating every new cognitive technology as categorically different from the ones before it.
    </p>

    <h2>Connect</h2>
    <p>
      Find me on <a href="https://linkedin.com/in/joe-fuqua" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn</a>, or subscribe to <a href="/algorithm-and-blues">Algorithm &amp; Blues</a> for weekly writing on AI governance and the long arc of technological change.
    </p>
  </div>
